    script: "Good evening. A new community composting initiative is being launched in the city of Maplewood this spring, and organizers say it could divert up to thirty percent of the city's organic waste from landfills within its first year. The program, called 'Green Bins for Maplewood,' will distribute free composting bins to every household in the city beginning April first. Residents will be able to place food scraps, yard waste, and biodegradable materials in the bins, which will be collected every two weeks by municipal crews.\n\nThe initiative was spearheaded by city councillor Diane Okoro, who says she was inspired after visiting a similar program in the city of Guelph that reduced landfill waste by twenty-two percent in just eight months. 'We produce an enormous amount of organic waste that doesn't need to end up in a landfill,' Councillor Okoro said at a press conference yesterday. 'Composting is one of the most effective and affordable ways for a municipality to reduce its environmental footprint.'\n\nThe program will cost the city an estimated one point two million dollars in its first year, funded through a reallocation of the existing waste management budget. Critics, however, argue that the money would be better spent on upgrading the city's aging recycling infrastructure, which has seen processing delays of up to three weeks in recent months. Despite the debate, a recent survey showed that sixty-eight percent of Maplewood residents support the composting program.",
