    script: "Good evening. Health officials across Ontario are issuing a warning following a significant rise in influenza cases among children under twelve. According to the latest FluWatch report from the Public Health Agency of Canada, the number of children hospitalized with flu complications this season has already exceeded last year's total — and we are only halfway through the flu season.\n\nDr. Isaac Bogoch, an infectious disease specialist at Toronto General Hospital, says this year's dominant strain, Influenza A, is particularly aggressive in younger patients. He warns that the flu can lead to serious secondary infections, including pneumonia and ear infections, which may require hospitalization.\n\nHealth officials are urging parents to ensure all children over six months of age receive the flu vaccine immediately if they have not already. Children under five, the elderly, pregnant women, and those with underlying conditions such as asthma or diabetes are considered at the highest risk.\n\nSymptoms parents should watch for include a sudden fever above thirty-eight-point-five degrees Celsius, severe fatigue, body aches, and a persistent cough. Unlike a common cold, flu symptoms appear very quickly and more severely.\n\nDr. Bogoch also emphasized that keeping sick children home from school is critical to prevent community spread. Children should remain home for at least twenty-four hours after their fever breaks without fever-reducing medication.\n\nFree flu vaccines are available at most pharmacies and public health clinics. Appointments can be booked online or by calling your local health unit.",
