    videoScene: "<h4>🎬 Video Scene Description</h4><p>Three coworkers — Raj, Sophia, and Tyler — are standing around a high-top table in a modern open-plan office. Behind them, a large window shows a city skyline at midday. Each has a tablet or phone in hand. A poster on the wall reads 'Customer Satisfaction Week.' Raj is gesturing expressively while speaking.</p>",
    script: "Raj: So, the customer satisfaction survey results are in, and honestly, they're a mixed bag. Overall satisfaction dropped from eighty-two percent last quarter to seventy-six percent this quarter. We need to figure out why and what we're going to do about it.\n\nSophia: I looked at the breakdown. The biggest drops were in two areas: response time and issue resolution. Customers said they're waiting an average of four minutes on hold before speaking to an agent, up from two minutes last quarter. And about thirty percent said their issue wasn't fully resolved on the first call.\n\nTyler: Those numbers are concerning. On the response time side, I think the issue is staffing. We lost three agents last month and haven't replaced them yet. The remaining team is stretched thin, especially during the eleven AM to two PM rush.\n\nRaj: I agree we need to hire, but that takes time. What can we do, um, in the short term to bring that hold time down?\n\nSophia: We could implement a callback system. Instead of waiting on hold, customers leave their number, and an agent calls them back within a specified window — say, thirty minutes. It's a better experience, and it reduces the pressure on the live queue.\n\nTyler: I like that idea. For the resolution issue, I think we need better training materials. A lot of the newer agents don't know how to handle complex cases, so they either escalate unnecessarily or give incomplete answers.\n\nRaj: Fair point. Let's create a knowledge base — a searchable database with step-by-step solutions for the fifty most common issues. That way, agents can quickly find accurate answers during a call.\n\nSophia: That's a great idea, Raj. I can start compiling the top issues from our ticket system. Tyler, could you work with the training team on updating the onboarding curriculum?\n\nTyler: Absolutely. I'll set up a meeting with them this week.\n\nRaj: Perfect. Let's aim to have both the callback system and the knowledge base in place within four weeks. I want to see those numbers back above eighty percent by next quarter.",
