    time: 360,
    desc: "You will hear a discussion between three people. Listen carefully and answer the questions.",
    videoScene: "<h4>🎬 Video Scene Description</h4><p>Three people — Linda (moderator), Kevin, and Sophie — are seated around a small round table in a community centre meeting room. A whiteboard behind them reads 'Community Garden Hours Review.' Linda has an agenda sheet in front of her. Kevin is leaning forward with his arms on the table. Sophie sits upright with her arms crossed.</p>",
    script: "Linda: Thanks everyone for coming. We're here to discuss whether the Ridgewood Community Garden should extend its access hours from the current six AM to eight PM schedule to the proposed five AM to ten PM. Sophie and Kevin, you've both been vocal on opposite sides. Kevin, let's start with you.\n\nKevin: Thanks, Linda. I'm a landscaper and often work long days in summer. The only time I can realistically get to my plot is early morning or after work. Right now I arrive at eight fifteen and find the gates already locked. Extending to five AM and ten PM would make a real difference for working people like me.\n\nSophie: I understand Kevin's frustration, but I live directly behind the garden fence and have two young kids in bed by eight. The current hours already occasionally cause issues — people talking, running water, tools clanging. Pushing to ten PM means two more hours of noise every evening. That's not reasonable.\n\nKevin: Most gardeners are quiet people. We could put in a noise guideline — anything electrical stops at eight, but people could water and tend plants quietly until ten.\n\nSophie: That's a reasonable compromise, I'll admit. But who enforces it? There's no on-site staff after seven PM now.\n\nLinda: The Parks Department mentioned they could introduce a volunteer community steward role — a rotating two-hour supervision shift taken on by garden members each month. Would that address your concern, Sophie?\n\nSophie: If it's well-organized and consistent, yes, I could support a limited extension — maybe nine PM, not ten. That feels more balanced.\n\nKevin: Nine PM works for me. That gives me enough time after work.\n\nLinda: Great. It sounds like we have a potential consensus around extending to nine PM with a noise guideline and a volunteer steward system. I'll bring this to the Parks Department for formal approval.",
